ddxv1Location.description:
Location specifies the position of a field on the input image and the position of a field on the dewarped document.
Both polygon and box coordinates are relative to their respective image dimensions, and are all in range 0-1.
E.g if an image resolution is 800x600 and x and y coordinates are 0.25 and 0.5 respectively, they translate
to absolute coordinates of 200x300 = (800 * 0.25)x(600 * 0.5).

status.description:
Status of the verification, we expect to have one or two images in the input request, and these images
are expected to be front and back sides of the SAME document. If it is a "one sided document" (e.g. most passports)
then only one image is expected in the input request. If it is a "two sided document" (e.g. most ID cards)
then two images are expected in the input request. If verification process was successfully performed
the status will be STATUS_OK. For the case of two sided document status will be STATUS_OK if we successfully
recognized both sides of the document. If back side is not recognized STATUS_MISSING_BACK_SIDE is returned, if
front side is not recognized STATUS_MISSING_FRONT_SIDE is returned. In the case of the "one sided document" the
status will be STATUS_OK if we successfully recognized the document and STATUS_DOCUMENT_RECOGNITION_FAILED
otherwise.

dvv1VerificationResultStatus.description:
- STATUS_OK: Verification performed successfully
 - STATUS_DOCUMENT_RECOGNITION_FAILED: Failed to recognize the document in the given images
 - STATUS_MISSING_BACK_SIDE: Found front side of the document but missing back side
 - STATUS_MISSING_FRONT_SIDE: Found back side of the document but missing front side
dvv1VerificationResultStatus.title: Status enum

textField.title:
field holds detected document textual fields.
Textual fields are all the fields that have textual representation and we expect
out users to use the OCRed and transcribed text.
Will be empty if status is not OK

visualField.description:
visualField holds detected document visual fields.
Visual fields are those whose values can't be extracted as text, and are
expected to be extracted as an image or position in the given image.

dateField.description:
dateField holds detected document date fields.
Compared to textual fields, they don't just hold textual information present on the document
but offer "date" in a structured parsed format (year, month, day) regardless of textual
representation.

sexField.description:
sexField if successfully detected, holds read and parsed sex field
Compared to textual fields, they don't just hold textual information present on the document
but offer gender information as a parsed enumeration.

imageQualityResult.title:
Image quality result, checking for blur, glare and hand over document
If image quality checks were NOT performed, this field is not set

liveness.title: Liveness result, if liveness checks were NOT performed, this field is not set

v1ImageChecks.title: Result of performing checks on input image

blurConfidenceLevel.title:
Blur Confidence Level, starts with level 0 that can be interpreted as "no blur"
Level 1 and above can be interpreted as "blur". The higher the level it means that is a higher
confidence in the model prediction

glareConfidenceLevel.title:
Glare Confidence Level, starts with level 0 that can be interpreted as "no glare"
Level 1 and above can be interpreted as "glare". The higher the level it means that is a higher
confidence in the model prediction

photocopy.description:
PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_NOT_PHOTOCOPY means that the input image is likely not a photocopy.
Level 1 and higher can be interpreted as "photocopy", the higher the level the higher the confidence in the model
prediction.
Using lower levels to detect photocopies will yield higher recall (i.e. you are less likely to "miss" a photocopy)
but at the cost of lower precision (i.e. you are more likely to detect a non-photocopy as a photocopy).
If you are looking for higher precision, use higher levels to detect photocopies.

screen.description:
SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_NOT_SCREEN means that the input image is likely not a screen
Level 1 and higher can be interpreted as "screen", the higher the level the higher the confidence in the model
prediction
Using lower levels to detect screens will yield higher recall (i.e. you are less likely to "miss" a screen)
but at the cost of lower precision (i.e. you are more likely to detect a non-screen as a screen).
If you are looking for higher precision, use higher levels to detect screens.

v1Liveness.title: Updated Liveness message using confidence levels

v1MatchCheck.description:
- MATCH_CHECK_NOT_PERFORMED: MATCH_CHECK_NOT_PERFORMED means that the match check was not performed
 - MATCH_CHECK_MATCHED: MATCH_CHECK_MATCHED data check was performed and matched
 - MATCH_CHECK_MISSMATCH: MATCH_CHECK_MISSMATCH data check was performed and did not match
v1MatchCheck.title: MatchCheck enum

fields.title: fields - data decoded from MRZ. Empty if status is STATUS_INVALID_FORMAT

mrzCode.description:
"Raw" mrz code, value that we OCR-ed from the document and decoded in "fields" field.
Depending on MRZ type, this field will contain one, two or three string values.

notValid.title: MRZ if found, decoded but not valid. This indicates serious validity issues with the document

missing.title: MRZ should be present on the document, but was not found

v1MrzFields.title:
MrzFields - a set of fields extracted from MRZ. Any of the fields can be empty!!
Depending on what was stored in the MRZ

v1MrzStatus.description:
- STATUS_OK: Mrz successfully detected, read and parsed
 - STATUS_INVALID_FORMAT: Mrz successfully detected, but value that was OCR-ed was not a valid MRZ format
 - STATUS_CHECK_DIGIT_INVALID: Mrz successfully detected, read but checksum digits did not match the content encoded in the MRZ
v1MrzStatus.title: Mrz Status

jurisdictionSpecifiedVehicleClass.description:
JurisdictionSpecifiedVehicleClass denotes the vehicle class specified by the jurisdiction.
Available only for DL documents.

jurisdictionSpecifiedRestrictionCodes.description:
JurisdictionSpecifiedRestrictionCodes represents codes that indicate
restrictions to driving privileges (e.g., airbrakes, automatic transmission). (b. DCB)
Available only for DL documents.

jurisdictionSpecifiedEndorsementCodes.description:
JurisdictionSpecifiedEndorsementCodes represents codes that signify
additional privileges granted to the cardholder beyond the vehicle class. (c. DCD)
Available only for DL documents.

documentExpirationDate.title:
DocumentExpirationDate denotes the date on which the driving and identification
privileges granted by the document are no longer valid. (MMDDCCYY for U.S.,
CCYYMMDD for Canada). (d. DBA)

customerFamilyName.title:
CustomerFamilyName indicates the family name of the cardholder (sometimes
called "last name" or "surname"). (e. DCS)

customerFirstName.title: CustomerFirstName denotes the first name of the cardholder. (f. DAC)

customerMiddleNames.title:
CustomerMiddleNames represents the middle name(s) of the cardholder;
if there are multiple middle names, they shall be separated by a comma. (g. DAD)

documentIssueDate.title:
DocumentIssueDate indicates the date on which the document was issued.
(MMDDCCYY for U.S., CCYYMMDD for Canada). (h. DBD)

dateOfBirth.title:
DateOfBirth denotes the date on which the cardholder was born.
(MMDDCCYY for U.S., CCYYMMDD for Canada). (i. DBB)

gender.title:
Gender represents the gender of the cardholder; 1 = male,
2 = female, 9 = not specified. (j. DBC)

eyeColor.title: EyeColor indicates the color of the cardholder's eyes using ANSI D-20 codes. (k. DAY)

height.title: Height represents the height of the cardholder; inches (in) or centimeters (cm). (l. DAU)

addressStreet1.title: AddressStreet1 denotes the street portion of the cardholder's address. (m. DAG)

addressCity.title: AddressCity indicates the city portion of the cardholder's address. (n. DAI)

jurisdictionCode.title: JurisdictionCode represents the state portion of the cardholder's address. (o. DAJ)

postalCode.title:
PostalCode indicates the postal code portion of the cardholder's address in the U.S.
and Canada, using zeros to fill any trailing portion up to nine digits if unknown. (p. DAK)

customerId.title: CustomerID represents a number assigned or calculated by the issuing authority. (q. DAQ)

documentDiscriminator.title:
DocumentDiscriminator uniquely identifies a particular document issued to that customer
from others that may have been issued in the past; serves multiple purposes including
document discrimination, audit information number, and/or inventory control. (r. DCF)

countryIdentification.title: CountryIdentification indicates the country in which DL/ID is issued; U.S. = USA, Canada = CAN. (s. DCG)

familyNameTruncation.title:
FamilyNameTruncation indicates whether a field has been truncated: T = truncated,
N = not truncated, U = unknown if truncated. (t. DDE)

firstNameTruncation.title:
FirstNameTruncation indicates whether a field has been truncated: T = truncated,
N = not truncated, U = unknown if truncated. (u. DDF)

middleNameTruncation.title:
MiddleNameTruncation indicates whether a field has been truncated: T = truncated,
N = not truncated, U = unknown if truncated. (v. DDG)

v1PhotocopyConfidenceLevel.description:
Photocopy Confidence Level Enum
PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_NOT_PHOTOCOPY means that the input image is likely not a photocopy.
Level 1 and higher can be interpreted as "photocopy", the higher the level the higher the confidence in the model
prediction.
Using lower levels to detect photocopies will yield higher recall (i.e. you are less likely to "miss" a photocopy)
but at the cost of lower precision (i.e. you are more likely to detect a non-photocopy as a photocopy).
If you are looking for higher precision, use higher levels to detect photocopies.

 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_NOT_PHOTOCOPY: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_0
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_1: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_1
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_2: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_2
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_3: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_3
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_4: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_4
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_5: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_5
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_6: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_6
 - PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_7: PHOTOCOPY_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_7

v1ScreenConfidenceLevel.description:
Screen Confidence Level Enum
SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_NOT_SCREEN means that the input image is likely not a screen
Level 1 and higher can be interpreted as "screen", the higher the level the higher the confidence in the model
prediction.
Using lower levels to detect screens will yield higher recall (i.e. you are less likely to "miss" a screen)
but at the cost of lower precision (i.e. you are more likely to detect a non-screen as a screen).
If you are looking for higher precision, use higher levels to detect screens.

 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_NOT_SCREEN: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_NOT_SCREEN
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_1: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_1
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_2: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_2
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_3: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_3
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_4: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_4
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_5: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_5
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_6: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_6
 - SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_7: SCREEN_CONFIDENCE_LEVEL_7

v1TextField.description: TextField - contains information of a single field detection on a document.

type.title: The type of the text field

checks.title: The checks for the text field

v1TextFieldType.description:
Type - an enum specifying field type. Eg. "First name", "Last name", "Address", etc.

 - TYPE_FIRST_NAME: Represents the first name of an individual
 - TYPE_LAST_NAME: Represents the last name of an individual
 - TYPE_NATIONALITY: Represents the nationality of an individual
 - TYPE_DOCUMENT_IDENTITY_NUMBER: Represents the unique number assigned to a document
 - TYPE_ISSUING_AUTHORITY: Represents the authority that issued a document
 - TYPE_ADDRESS: Represents the address of an individual
 - TYPE_PERSONAL_IDENTITY_NUMBER: Represents a unique personal identification number, such as OIB
 - TYPE_MARITAL_STATUS: Represents the marital status of an individual
 - TYPE_EXTENDED_ADDRESS: Represents additional information about an address
 - TYPE_EXTENDED_ADDRESS_SPECIFICS: Represents additional information about an address (second part)
 - TYPE_CLASS: Represents a classification or category
 - TYPE_CONDITIONS: Represents conditions or restrictions
 - TYPE_ENDORSEMENTS: Represents endorsements or special permissions
 - TYPE_DRIVERS_LICENSE_TYPE: Represents the type of licence or permit
 - TYPE_FULL_NAME: Represents the full name of an individual
 - TYPE_PLACE_OF_BIRTH: Represents the place of birth of an individual
 - TYPE_PROFESSION: Represents the profession or occupation of an individual
 - TYPE_EMPLOYER: Represents the employer of an individual
 - TYPE_EXTENDED_NAME: Represents additional information about a name
 - TYPE_FATHERS_NAME: Represents the father's name of an individual
 - TYPE_MOTHERS_NAME: Represents the mother's name of an individual
 - TYPE_RACE: Represents the race or ethnicity of an individual
 - TYPE_RESIDENTIAL_TYPE: Represents the residential status of an individual
 - TYPE_RESTRICTIONS: Represents restrictions or limitations
 - TYPE_BLOOD_TYPE: Represents the blood type of an individual
 - TYPE_NUMBER: Represents an additional numbers/codes that can appear on some documents
